message: /* A Commons file used on this page or its Wikidata item has been nominated for deletion */
/* Sacred grounds */ Expanded through data from the article, Anito.
/* Shrines, altars, and sacred areas */ In some areas, such practices are still prevalent especially among indigenous communities in the Cordilleras, Palawan, Mindanao, and highland Panay.

/* Shrines, altars, and sacred areas */ In some places, spirit houses can be both semi-permanent and permanent. However, they need reconstruction in the long-run as the materials used are perishable (such as bamboo).
/* Fleeing from the Philippines to Hawaii */
The terms that are used to refer to the religious buildings among the indigenous religions in the Philippines are both "shrine" and "spirit house".

/* Altars and sacred areas */ Temples, in a foreign sense (Buddhist, etc), were not present in the Philippines, however, shrines, in an indigenous Filipino context (aka "spirit houses") were indeed present as noted by some scholars such as Scott (1994) in his book Barangay (page 90).

/* Philippines */ Reinstated portions with proper sources provided, namely "Philippine Folklore Stories, John Maurice Miller, 1904", "Hill, P. (1934). Philippine Short Stories. Manila: Oriental Commercial Company", and "Jocano, F. L. (1969). Philippine Mythology. Quezon City: Capitol Publishing House Inc." Sources from Aswang Project, not reinstated.
